asing; beloved; attractive’ (Old English <i>swēte</i>, <i>swōt</i>), from which the personal names derive. Compare   Swett  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Suess   and French   Ledoux   ‘the gentle, the sweet’."],"variants":[{"name":"Sweeting","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Sweting</i> (Old English <i>Swēting</i>, a derivative of <i>swēte</i> ‘sweet’; see   Sweet  ).","nickname from Middle English <i>sweting</i> ‘darling, sweetheart’, used for a popular and attractive person, or for someone who habitually addressed people with the term."]},{"name":"Swett","meanings":["Altered form of English   Sweet  . This surname is also found in Chile, where it is at least in part of North American origin.","Americanized (possibly shortened) form of an unidentified eastern Ashkenazic surname.","Americanized form of Polish   Szwed  ."]},{"name":"Sott","meanings":["English and Scottish: nickname from Middle English <i>sot</i>, Old English <i>sott</i> ‘foolish’, also commonly used as a noun denoting a foolish person.","English and Scottish: nickname from Middle English <i>sot(e)</i>, <i>swot(e)</i>, Old English <i>swōt</i> ‘sweet, pleasant, beloved’, also used as a noun meaning ‘dear one’. Compare   Sweet  .","English and Scottish: nickname from Middle English and Old English <i>sōt</i>, Old Norse <i>sót</i> ‘soot’, also used as an adjective ‘sooty’, perhaps given to someone with black hair. Among the Scandinavians it was used as a personal name, <i>Sóti</i>, which was brought to England by the Vikings."]},{"name":"Sweat","meanings":["English: variant of   Sweet  ."]},{"name":"Sweatt","meanings":["English: variant of   Sweet  ."]}]},{"name":"Phillip","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Philip  , in part a reflection of the surname, which is usually spelled <i>Phillips</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":74,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":83,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Phillip John Sweet was born in 1475, in Modbury, Devon, England, his father, Sir Thomas Swete, was 50 and his mother, Lady Curry Rivel, was 52. He had at least 2 sons with Mrs Phillip John Sweet. He died in 1561, in Devon, England, at the age of 86."},"et":{"1475–1561":"1475–1561","1450–1512":"1450–1512","1480–Male":"1480–Surnud","1475–Female":"1475–Surnud","1506–1547":"1506–1547","1519–Male":"1519–Surnud","1425–1487":"1425–1487","1423–1500":"1423–1500","29 May 1500":"29. mai 1500","1561":"1561","1450":"1450","1480":"1480","1558":"1558","1547":"1547","about 1519":"umbes 1519","1425":"1425","27 February 1